# Extreme Events and Realized Volatility Forecasting: Information Augmentation in Linear and Nonlinear Models

## Objective

This project studies whether intraday extreme-return information improves daily realized volatility (RV) forecasting for crypto assets.

The key methodological constraint is a fair comparison between:
1. HAR (linear, aggregated-information representation), and
2. LSTM (nonlinear, raw sequential-information representation),

using the same target, same rolling train/test windows, and same underlying daily information set.

The workflow combines:

1. Daily RV construction from 5-minute Binance data.
2. Extreme-event detection from intraday returns using rolling quantile regression.
3. Daily aggregation of event intensity features.
4. Rolling-window forecast comparison between linear (HAR) and nonlinear (LSTM) models.
5. Forecast comparison using statistical tests (Diebold-Mariano and Model Confidence Set).

